import java.util.Stack;

public int minOperationsToFlip(String expression) {
    Stack<Integer> zero = new Stack<>(), one = new Stack<>(), op = new Stack<>();
    zero.push(0);
    one.push(0);
    for (char c : expression.toCharArray()) {
        if (c == '&') op.push(1);
        else if (c == '|') op.push(2);
        else if (Character.isDigit(c)) {
            if (c == '0') {
                one.push(1);
                zero.push(0);
            } else {
                zero.push(1);
                one.push(0);
            }
        } else if (c == ')') {
            int cur_op = op.pop();
            int new_zero, new_one;
            int x = zero.pop();
            int y = one.pop() + 1;
            if (cur_op == 1) {
                new_zero = Math.max(x, y);
                new_one = one.peek() + Math.min(x, zero.peek());
            } else {
                new_zero = zero.peek() + Math.min(x, one.peek());
                new_one = Math.max(y, one.peek());
            }
            zero.pop();
            one.pop();
            zero.push(new_zero);
            one.push(new_one);
        }
    }
    return zero.peek() + 1;
}
```

    1. Create three stacks for zero, one, and operation.
2. Iterate through the characters in the expression.
3. For each character, follow the rules:
   * If it is '&', push the value 1 to the operation stack.
   * If it is '|', push the value 2 to the operation stack.
   * If it is a digit (0 or 1), update the one and zero stacks accordingly.
   * If it is a closing parentheses, retrieve the operation and update the one and zero stacks based on the operation value.
4. At the end of the iteration, the last value in the zero stack + 1 is the required minimum cost to change the final value of the expression.
